{{refimprove|date=February 2016}}
[[File:2009 Malaysian Grand Prix start (cropped).jpg|thumb|250px|A standing start during the [[2009 Malaysian Grand Prix]].]]
A '''standing start''' is a type of start in [[auto racing]] events, in which cars are stationary when the race begins.

==Procedure==
In a standing start, cars are completely still but with their engines running when a green signal is given to start the race. This is often preceded by a set number of lights. Standing starts are common in many [[motorsports]], including most single-seater ([[Formula One]] and [[GP2 Series]] notably), Touring Cars (most notably [[British Touring Car Championship|British]] and [[World Touring Car Championship|World]] Touring Cars), [[drag racing]], the [[Supercars Championship]], [[kart racing]], and many types of short-course [[off-road racing]]. The standing start often occurs following a [[parade lap]].{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}

American-based series such as [[IndyCar]], [[NASCAR]], and [[Sports Car Club of America|SCCA]] have traditionally utilized rolling starts. During the 2013 and 2014 seasons, the [[IndyCar Series]] adopted a rule for standing starts on a trial basis for selected events.<ref>{{cite web|last=Glendenning|first=Mark|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/108699|title=IndyCar updates 2013 standing start procedure|publisher=[[Autosport]]|date=July 9, 2013|accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=DiZinno|first=Tony|url=http://motorsportstalk.nbcsports.com/2013/10/01/grand-prix-of-indianapolis-set-for-may-10-2014-on-revised-course/related/|title=Grand Prix of Indianapolis set for May 10, 2014 on revised course|publisher=[[NBC Sports]]|date=October 1, 2013|accessdate=2013-10-01}}</ref> IndyCar dropped the procedure after the 2014 season, due to numerous start aborts and a start-line crash at the 2014 [[IndyCar Grand Prix|Grand Prix of Indianapolis]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Olson|first1=Jeff|title=IndyCar eliminates standing starts in 2015|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/motor/indycar/2014/12/02/indycar-double-points-races-in-2015-rules-changes/19782467/|accessdate=11 October 2017|work=[[USA Today]]|date=December 2, 2014}}</ref>

==Le Mans==
[[Image:1965-05-23 Le-Mans-Start 3.jpg|thumb|Le Mans-style start at the [[Nürburgring]] in 1965.]]
A [[24 Hours of Le Mans|Le Mans]]-style start was used for many years in various types of motor racing.  When the start flag dropped, drivers had to run across the track to their cars which were parked on the other side, climb in, start the car, and drive away to begin the race.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}

[[File:Départ 04686.JPG|thumb|left|Cars starting from "launch point" at the 2013 EFRA European 1:8 IC Off-Road Championship.]]
Such starts were very unsafe, with drivers possibly rushing the process of fastening their safety equipment. Britain's [[Royal Automobile Club|RAC]] prohibited the use of the Le Mans start in English racing in late summer 1962 precisely for this reason.<ref name=IMS1062>{{cite magazine | ref = IMS10 | title = Från skilda fronter |trans-title=From different fronts | page = 30 | language = Swedish | editor-last = Björklund | editor-first = Bengt | location = Lerum, Sweden | magazine = Illustrerad Motor Sport | number = 10 | date = October 1962 }}</ref> As a result, they are no longer used in any motorsport except for endurance [[motorcycle racing]], such as the [[Coke Zero]] [[Suzuka 8 Hours]] and the [[24 Hours of Le Mans (motorcycle race)|24 Heures Moto]], bicycle endurance races, [[Kinetic Sculpture Race|Kinetic Sculpture Races]]<ref name="KB2016">{{Cite web  | title = Baltimore Kinetic Sculpture Race 2016 Race Report  |  url=http://www.kineticbaltimore.com/KSR/2016  | accessdate = 13 May 2017}}</ref> and due to their vulnerability to [[flameout]]<nowiki/>s, in nitro powered [[Radio-controlled car|radio-controlled]] racing, except they are held above ground until start by its mechanics whilst the drivers remain in their stand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ifmar.org/pdf/rules/ifmar_wc_8th_track_2013.pdf|title=IFMAR 1/8th I.C. Track Racing and Technical Rules|last1=|first1=|last2=|first2=|date=|website=|publisher=[[International Federation of Model Auto Racing]]|page=11|accessdate=2014-12-01|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141101231613/http://www.ifmar.org/pdf/rules/ifmar_wc_8th_track_2013.pdf|archivedate=2014-11-01|df=}}</ref>

[[File:LandRushStartIceRacingLakeSinissippi2010.jpg|thumb|Land rush start (2010).]]
A Le Mans start variation called a "land rush start" is used at [[Off-road racing|short course off-road races]] at [[Crandon International Off-Road Raceway]] where the vehicles start lined up side-by-side on a wide part of the track.  The "land rush start" is based on the 1970 24 Hours of Le Mans start, and is used in historic races at Le Mans in some situations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.off-roadweb.com/tech/0402or_corr_off_road_racing/index.html|title=Land-Rush Start Sets Tone for High-Speed Weekend|last=Blumer|first=Kevin|date=February 2009|publisher=Off-Road magazine|accessdate=2010-03-01}}</ref> However, unlike the true Le Mans start, engines are already running and the drivers are already sitting behind the wheel, wearing their [[safety belt]]s, when the starting signal is displayed.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}

A second variation is used in the [[Australian GT Championship]] invitational Highlands 101 at Highlands Motorsports Park in New Zealand. It integrates both the Le Mans start and the Land Rush start.  The drivers are behind the wheel already, but the co-drivers are equipped with flags approximately {{convert|250|m|km ft}} from their cars on the entrance to pit lane.  At the signal, the co-drivers run the {{convert|250|m|km mi}} and hand over a flag that signals to their team the car is cleared to start.  The driver then starts the car.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}

==Safety and precautions==
The alternative to a standing start is a [[rolling start]]. Standing starts are often deemed safer in Formula sports, due to the higher acceleration speeds, which could cause problems if a rolling start were used, based on the speed of the safety car and regulations regarding the start (some forms of motorsport are strict on when cars may accelerate after the safety car enters pit lane—some do not permit acceleration until the cars are near the start line at starter's orders). A standing start can cause problems, however, such as stalled cars being hit by the driver who starts behind them on the grid. One example of that was the [[2007 Champ Car Mont-Tremblant]], where multiple cars stalled on the start, resulting in a safety car. Motorsports using standing starts usually penalize drivers who "jump the start" by moving before the lights are extinguished.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}

